		<div class="inner clearfix">
			<div class="col-md-11 col-sm-11 col-xs-12 no-padding">
				<h1>Java zero day = time to disable Java, in your browser at least</h1>
<div class="excerpt">Now is the time to disable Java in your web browser, or even remove it from your system if that is practical. Why? The bad guys are hard at work trying to exploit a zero day vulnerability in the latest version of Java (version 1.7, Update 6.). This vulnerability is the subject of a US-CERT</div>
<div class="post-meta">
    <div class="wls-authors">
            </div>
    <span class="meta">
		<span class="strong">
			<time datetime="2012-08-29 12:34:25">29 Aug 2012 - 12:34PM</time>
		</span>
			</span>
</div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</div>
</div>	

            <div class="content">
                <div class="social-wrapper" id="social-sharer">
                    <span class="text">Share</span>
	<a class="share-facebook" href="https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.welivesecurity.com%2F2012%2F08%2F29%2Fdisabling-java-a-safer-way-to-browse%2F" target="blank" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="top" data-original-title="Share on Facebook">
